          <jats:p>The outflow of prior confined or intruded liquid from a hydrophobic pore at the nanoscale is the foundation for devising nanofluidics-enabled, reusable functional materials, structures, and devices and is fundamentally different from that at the macroscale due to nanoconfinement effects. We, in both molecular-dynamics simulations and experiments, addressed the nanoconfinement mechanism that hinders the outflow of nanoconfined various liquid by investigating both inflow and outflow processes of liquid in hydrophobic nanopores and demonstrated that a continuous and spontaneous outflow with high and stable efficiency could be achieved. The elucidated outflow mechanisms and regulation strategies will provide a rational route for exploring high-performance reusable devices in a broad scope of nanoporous materials and liquid environments by leveraging unique nanopore–liquid interactions.</jats:p>
